1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
FOR
4 HOUSE BILL NO. 4060 By: Alonso-Sandoval
5
6
7 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
8 An Act relating to the Corporation Commission;
creating the Plug-In Solar Power Amendments Act;
9 defining terms; making certain exemptions;
prohibiting electric utilities from making certain
10 requirements of users; providing for safety
standards; limiting certain liability; creating
11 certain responsibility; authorizing the adoption of
certain rules; prohibiting certain aspects of rules;
12 limiting applicability of act; providing for
codification; and providing an effective date.
13
14
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 875 of Title 17, unless there is
19 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Plug-In Solar
21 Power Amendments Act".
22 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 876 of Title 17, unless there is
24 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
Req. No. 16983 Page 1

1 As used in this act:
2 1. "Electric utility" means any public utility providing retail
3 electric service subject to the jurisdiction of the Oklahoma
4 Corporation Commission.
5 2. "Portable solar generation device" means a solar
6 photovoltaic device that:
7 a. has a rated alternating current output capacity of not
8 more than one thousand two hundred (1,200) watts in
9 the aggregate,
10 b. is designed to connect to a customer's premises wiring
11 through a standard grounded one hundred twenty-volt
12 electrical outlet,
13 c. includes integrated anti-islanding or equivalent
14 safety functionality that prevents energizing a
15 building's electrical system during a power outage,
16 and
17 d. is intended primarily to offset electricity consumed
18 on the premises of the retail electric customer.
19 3. "Retail electric customer" means a residential customer
20 receiving electric service from an electric utility.
21 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 877 of Title 17, unless there is
23 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24
Req. No. 16983 Page 2

1 A portable solar generation device that meets the requirements
2 of this act:
3 1. Shall not be considered an interconnection under state law
4 or Oklahoma Corporation Commission rules;
5 2. Shall not be subject to net metering statutes, tariffs, or
6 programs; and
7 3. Shall not require an interconnection agreement, application,
8 inspection, or approval from an electric utility or the Oklahoma
9 Corporation Commission.
10 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
11 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 878 of Title 17, unless there is
12 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
13 An electric utility shall not require a retail electric customer
14 using a qualifying portable solar generation device to:
15 1. Obtain prior authorization or permission from the utility;
16 2. Pay any fee, charge, or tariff related to the installation
17 or use of the device;
18 3. Install additional metering, controls, or equipment beyond
19 what is integrated into the device;
20 4. Execute an interconnection, net metering, or service
21 modification agreement; or
22 5. Purchase insurance or provide indemnification related to the
23 device.
24
Req. No. 16983 Page 3

1 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 879 of Title 17, unless there is
3 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A portable solar generation device shall comply with nationally
5 recognized electrical safety standards, including anti-islanding
6 protection. Nothing in this act limits the authority of state or
7 local electrical inspectors to enforce generally applicable
8 electrical safety codes unrelated to utility interconnection.
9 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 880 of Title 17, unless there is
11 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 An electric utility shall not be liable for any damage, injury,
13 or loss caused by a portable solar generation device or the
14 installation, operation, or maintenance of such a device by a retail
15 electric customer. The retail electric customer bears
16 responsibility for the proper installation and maintenance of the
17 device and compliance with applicable safety standards.
18 SECTION 7. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 881 of Title 17, unless there is
20 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. The Oklahoma Corporation Commission may adopt administrative
22 rules solely as necessary to:
23 1. Enforce the provisions of this act; and
24 2. Ensure compliance with applicable safety standards.
Req. No. 16983 Page 4

1 B. Rules adopted under this section shall not:
2 1. Require registration, approval, or notification for portable
3 solar generation devices;
4 2. Impose fees or charges;
5 3. Reduce the maximum wattage authorized by statute; or
6 4. Subject such devices to net metering or interconnection
7 requirements.
8 SECTION 8. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
9 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 882 of Title 17, unless there is
10 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
11 Nothing in this act shall be construed to:
12 1. Authorize compensation for exported electricity;
13 2. Modify existing distributed generation or net metering
14 programs; or
15 3. Limit the authority of the Oklahoma Corporation Commission
16 over traditional interconnection of electric generation facilities.
17 SECTION 9. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
